Historical significance

Despite the second wave of feminism after World War One and the feminist movement coming to prominence in 1968 during the student uprising - divorce rights in United Kingdom have not proven to be a topic of discussion until today.

At present, women who want to file for divorce must cite fault (misconduct in marriage) or a no-fault ground (divorce after a certain amount of time). In 2000, the Divorce Bill finally passed the House of Commons, setting out to amend the then-current law. However, the bill was defeated in the House of Lords. Clearly, then, divorce rights in the UK are still difficult to achieve, despite having undergone many challenges. And both advancing the position of women and decreasing domestic violence attacks in the United Kingdom have hit a bump in the road. Women speak of feelings of insignificance in the matter so far, having pride in women's achievements over the years. Historically, the battle for divorce rights of married women began when their husbands had the right to kill their wives by pushing them in front of trains or pouring acid on them. The rate of domestic violence in the United Kingdom was at an all time high in the 1970's. As of today, however, the rate is still amazingly high, and needs to be addressed by the circuit court.
